d autobiographical research as well as the analysis of texts from internet forums and blogs, this monograph demonstrates the applications of the author’s original concept of 'anchoring', and its foregrounding of the combination of sociological and psychological perspectives. Rethinking settlement and integration aims not only to examine the processes of adaptation and settling among today’s migrants, but highlights practical implications to better support individuals facing changes and challenges in new, complex and fluid societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigration. 0aImmigrantsxCultural assimilation. 0aImmigrantsxSocial conditions. 0aPolish peoplexCultural assimilationzGreat BritainvCase studies. 0aUkrainiansxCultural assimilationzPolandvCase studies. 4aInternational Relations 2020. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aPolish migrants in the UK.  aUkrainian migrants in Poland.  aadaptation.  aanchoring.  aintegration.  asafety.  asecurity.  asettlement.  asettling.  astability.1 aGrzymala-Kazlowska, Aleksandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613684840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526136848423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526136848/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles